## Montecarlo Café, Buenos Aires, Argentina

Empanadas are a ubiquitous street food of Argentina, consisting of baked or fried dough surrounding meat or vegetables with a special crimp to seal the top edge. In Buenos Aires, they are usually cheap and fast.

In Buenos Aires (2023), one of our city experiences was a workshop on how to make empanadas in the basement of Café Montecarlo. Some say it was Che Guevara's favorite café. This recipe is from the chef there. The chef told us many countries claim to have invented empanadas, and perhaps they even came from China — from dumplings brought back by Marco Polo. Adding ajwain and coriander seeds turns the empanada into a samosa. Steaming it and filling it with pork and vegetables turns it into a dumpling. Make it a bit bigger and you get a Cornish pasty. Add tomatoes and you have a calzone.

Whether you are lost and alone or laughing with friends, I hope these empanadas will nourish you during a long walk.

---

The following recipe includes a single type of dough and multiple options for fillings. The volume of dough is correct for the volume of one filling and should make anywhere from 20–30 empanadas. I recommend looking up a video on how to fill and crimp empanadas.

## Dough

- 1 kg (2 lbs) flour
- 10 tbsp animal fat or corn oil
- 2 eggs
- Water
- ½ tbsp salt

## Fillings

### Beef

- Equal parts cubed beef and vegetables (onions, green onions, peppers, tomatoes)
- Spices: salt, cumin, chili powder, paprika
- 1 glass red wine
- 2 glasses vegetable broth

### Cheese

- 500 g (1 lb) Tybo cheese
- 250 g (½ lb) green onion
- Salt
- Chili powder

### Humita (Corn)

- 1 kg (2 lbs) fresh corn
- 250 g (½ lb) red pepper
- 250 g (½ lb) onion
- Salt, cinnamon, chili powder
- 50 ml (3⅓ tbsp) honey
- 100 g (¾ cup) flour
- 200 ml (1 cup) milk
- Some parmesan or goat cheese

---

## Instructions

### Dough

1. Mix all the dough ingredients in a large bowl.
2. Let the dough rest for at least an hour.
3. Ideally, roll the dough 30–50 times in a pasta machine, folding in the middle each time. Otherwise, roll out thin with a rolling pin.
4. Cut the dough into circular discs.

### Beef Filling

1. Chop the beef and vegetables.
2. Put all the ingredients in a pan with oil. Add the spices and let it cook for 15 minutes before adding the wine and vegetable broth. Stew for 50 minutes.
3. Add gelatin to keep the juice when filling the empanada.
4. Bake at 300°C (575°F) for 15 minutes.

### Cheese Filling

1. In a pan with corn oil, cook the onions and pepper for 10 minutes.
2. Add some salt and the cheese.
3. Fill the empanadas and bake at 300°C (575°F) for 15 minutes.

### Humita Filling

1. Grate half the kernels and keep the other half intact.
2. In a pan with butter and oil, cook the vegetables with the spices.
3. After a few minutes, add the corn, flour, milk, and honey.
4. In a pot, create a basket with the corn husks, and fill it with the humita and cheese.
5. Fill the empanadas and bake at 300°C (575°F) for 15 minutes.
